    <div class="ians-column">

      <h2>Unit Training Requirements</h2>

    </div>

    <div class="ians-column-wide-2">
      <div class="oj-photo-glass-text ians-bg-blue-dark">
        {% image "images/young-atco.jpg", "A young ATCO undergoing training."%}
        <div>
          <p>OJTIs deliver training at an ATC Unit. Unit training is the training that allows an <strong>ATC or student ATCO</strong> to acquire the practical skills and site-specific knowledge needed to perform the job of an air traffic controller <strong>at that unit</strong>.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="ians-column">

      <p>Every ATC unit must have a <strong>Unit Training Plan</strong> (UTP) that has been approved by the competent authority. The UTP contains the details of every ‘unit endorsement course’ that is provided at a unit.</p>

      {# <p class="oj-dev-notes">Not sure of the logic of which text gets made bold below.</p> #}

      <p>The UTP contains:</p>

      <ul class="oj-utp-list">
        <li>
          list of unit endorsement course(s), ratings and endorsements</li>
        <li>
          structure, training methods, min. duration,</li>
        <li>
          processes for conduct and adaptations of unit endorsement course(s)</li>
        <li>
          examinations &amp; assessments</li>
        <li>
          training personnel qualifications, roles, responsibilities</li>
        <li>
          early termination of training &amp; appeal process</li>
        <li>
          specific records</li>
        <li>
          list of abnormal/ emergency situations</li>
        <li>
          review process and reasons</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="oj-utp-list-title">
        <p>ATCO.D.055(b) + Supporting AMCs and GM</p>
      </div>

      <p>To undertake unit training the person <strong>must have</strong> either a Student ATCO Licence or an ATCO Licence.</p>

      <h2>Unit Endorsement Course</h2>

      <p>The ATCO Licensing regulation introduced the term ‘unit endorsement course’, however the structure and phases of such a course will be <strong>familiar</strong> to you as it is the same structure that units have been using for many years; Transitional, Pre-OJT and OJT phases.</p>

    </div>

